recordings.loc: Hulesjön, Falköpings soptipp, Falköping, Västra Götaland County
recordings.rmk: Aberrant song of a (apparent) Chiffchaff, holding territory during April-June in a area with some Salix bushes at the edge of small birch Betula pendula wood. The song was very constant, somewhat stuttering with almost Willow warbler-like parts, and hybrid Willow Warbler x Chiffchaff was considered as well as Iberian Chiffchaff. The site was rather unusual for Chiffchaff, which is rare in the region, and the bird looked somewhat odd (though seemingly within the variation of Common Chiffchaff, a few photos of the bird are available on www.artportalen.se), making a hybrid a possibility. It did respond strongly to song of Iberian chiffchaff, though I now find it not probable that it was that species.

at the rim of larger farm lands and mixed forest. - **sound was 
trapped** -  ...for 3 1/2 days -(sunday 29.09.-wendsday 02.10.2019)...each day between 4,30 h - 00,00 h a clock MEZ

...olympus LS_3 was fastend short above  ground direct inside under a pylon.

..**the analyze of all birds is not shure..couse all birds not seen**

day/time now:   **Monday‎30.09.2019--‏11,00-17,30 a clock MEZ**  -- here 2.nd part of day now: ...  still strong wind

**here**:  **from assumted distance to my recorder and storm intensity here..   the birds looked probably for shelter of the storm "inside the with withywind overgrown pylon"** .


Sitta europaea...probably while foraging .

[pictu. from this pylon](https://www.imgbox.de/users/Robinie/bine_1912/DSC_2246v_361vvvcomp.jpg)
 
...wheather was all: sunshine - rain - storm - cloudy to fine  .....these some days.

sunrise in bobingen was: 07,18 a clock

sunset was:  18,54 a clock

place: (  KusaWoid-W.W-WEG1link-staff2 aa  )

[all birds this timer-session you can hear here](https://www.xeno-canto.org/explore?query=rec%3A%20uhl%20loc%3A%20bobingen%20rmk%3A%20KusaWoidWwWEG1linkTaffIIaa)  .

[all recordings with twitching green bushcricket --Tettigonia cantans-- here](https://www.xeno-canto.org/explore?query=rec%3A%20uhl%20also%3A%20twitching)

background noise:  industry......and traffic of highway , sorry.

--  **a little help by all recordings with twitching green bushcricket [Tettigonia cantans]:**  turn on the loudness of your headspeakers loud till you hear the  "twitching green bushcricket [Tettigonia cantans]" quiet fine.

...i uploaded these more or less bad "XC-quality" sounds, cause..i wanted to document this "wood-habitat"...
holisticly. -- i filtered the cuts in a way that **the Birds-themselves are not  falsified from originaly cuts.**
